▣ 실습: One-dimensional Kriging example¶

※ 예제 문제¶

  • : 0~1
  • : y = (x - 6)2 sin(12x - 2)
  • : x=0, 0.4, 0.6, 1.0
  • Kriging
In [4]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from smt.surrogate_models import KRG
In [5]:
#  (DOE)
xt = np.array([0.0, 0.4, 0.6, 1.0]) #
In [6]:
#   ( or )
def HF_function(x): # high-fidelity function
    return ((x*6-2)**2)*np.sin((x*6-2)*2)
yt = HF_function(xt)
In [7]:
print("Input data",xt)
print("Output data",yt)

Input data [0.  0.4 0.6 1. ]
Output data [ 3.02720998  0.11477697 -0.14943781 15.82973195]
In [8]:
#  (Main process)
initial_theta = np.array([1e-2]) #   
sm = KRG(theta0 = initial_theta)
sm.set_training_values(xt, yt) #  
sm.train() #  

___________________________________________________________________________
   
                                  Kriging
___________________________________________________________________________
   
 Problem size
   
      # training points.        : 4
   
___________________________________________________________________________
   
 Training

   Training - done. Time (sec):  0.0888569
In [9]:
#  (Post-processing)
num = 100
x = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, num) # 0 1  num x 

y_true = HF_function(x)
#    
y_mean = sm.predict_values(x) # 
s2 = sm.predict_variances(x) #  


# add a plot with variance
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1)
axs.plot(x, y_true)
axs.plot(xt, yt, "o")
axs.plot(x, y_mean)
axs.fill_between(
    np.ravel(x),
    np.ravel(y_mean - 3 * np.sqrt(s2)), # -3 
    np.ravel(y_mean + 3 * np.sqrt(s2)), # +3 
    color="lightgrey",
)
axs.set_xlabel("x")
axs.set_ylabel("y")
axs.legend(
    ["True function","Training data","Mean prediction","99 % confidence Interval"], # 3  99 %  
    loc="best",
)
plt.show()

   Predicting - done. Time (sec):  0.0000000
   
   Prediction time/pt. (sec) :  0.0000000

s2_want = np.sqrt(sm.predict_variances(x_want)) #  
y_real = HF_function(x_want) # 
print(y_want,s2_want,y_real) # / /

In [13]:
#   (Pre-processing)
xt = np.array([0.0, 0.4, 0.6, 1.0]) #  
yt = HF_function(xt)

#  (Main process)
initial_theta = np.array([1e-2])
sm = KRG(theta0=initial_theta) #   
sm.set_training_values(xt, yt) #  
sm.train() #  

#  (Post-processing)
num = 100
x = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, num)


#    
y_mean = sm.predict_values(x) # 
s2 = sm.predict_variances(x) #  


# add a plot with variance
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1)
axs.plot(x, y_true)
axs.plot(xt, yt, "o")
axs.plot(x, y_mean)
axs.fill_between(
    np.ravel(x),
    np.ravel(y_mean - 3 * np.sqrt(s2)), # -3 
    np.ravel(y_mean + 3 * np.sqrt(s2)), # +3 
    color="lightgrey",
)
axs.set_xlabel("x")
axs.set_ylabel("y")
axs.legend(
    ["True function","Training data","Mean prediction","99 % confidence Interval"], # 3  99 %  
    loc="best",
)
plt.show()

#   (Pre-processing)
# xt = np.array([0.0, 0.4, 0.6, 1.0]) #  
xt = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, 8)
yt = HF_function(xt)

#  (Main process)
initial_theta = np.array([1e-2])
sm = KRG(theta0=initial_theta) #   
sm.set_training_values(xt, yt) #  
sm.train() #  

#  (Post-processing)
num = 100
x = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0, num)


#    
y_mean = sm.predict_values(x) # 
s2 = sm.predict_variances(x) #  

# add a plot with variance
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1)
axs.plot(x, y_true)
axs.plot(xt, yt, "o")
axs.plot(x, y_mean)
axs.fill_between(
    np.ravel(x),
    np.ravel(y_mean - 2 * np.sqrt(s2)), # -2 
    np.ravel(y_mean + 2 * np.sqrt(s2)), # +2 
    color="lightgrey",
)
axs.set_xlabel("x")
axs.set_ylabel("y")
axs.legend(
    ["True function","Training data","Mean prediction","95 % confidence Interval"], # 2  95 %  
    loc="best",
)
plt.show()
